District Judge Kow Keng Siong:

Introduction

1       Mdm. Lim Beng Kim, Lulu (“the Accused”) faces 36 charges under s 420 and s 477A of the Penal Code (Cap 224, 2008 Rev Ed) (“Penal Code”). Her offences have been described as “one of the largest and most complex fraudulent trade financing schemes ever to be prosecuted before the courts”.[note: 1] These schemes had spanned three years, defrauded 16 financial institutions (“the victims”), led to the grant of at least US$586.5 mil in credit facilities to the Accused’s company, caused the victims to suffer a staggering loss of more than US$469,102,278.91 (S$631,224,026.50),[note: 2] and tarnished Singapore’s reputation as a global commodity trading hub.

Background

Agritrade International Pte Ltd

3       At all material times, the Accused was the chief financial officer (“CFO”) and executive director of Agritrade International Pte Ltd (“AIPL”), a global trading house based in Singapore. AIPL’s businesses included trading and refining in commodities, as well as providing logistical support for regional land reclamation and construction projects. AIPL’s founder and the Accused’s boss was Ng Say Pek (“Ng”).[note: 4]

Funding for AIPL’s businesses

4       AIPL conducted its business through trade financing. Under this form of financing, AIPL would provide the financial institutions with documentary proof that it had entered into agreements to purchase/sell goods (e.g., invoices and shipping documents), and the financial institutions would then disburse funds to the appropriate party.[note: 5]

5       The Accused and Ng were responsible for securing trade financing facilities from the financial institutions. Both knew that in determining the credit line to be extended to AIPL, these institutions would rely on, among others, AIPL’s financial statements for the preceding financial years.

Falsified financial statements

6       The Accused’s charges involve three sets of falsified financial statements. These statements came about in the following circumstances:

(a)     Sometime in late 2016, late 2017, and late 2018, the Accused provided a copy of AIPL’s management accounts to Corporate Assurance PAC (“PAC”), an auditing and accounting firm. This was for the purpose of preparing a set of draft consolidated financial statements for AIPL and its subsidiaries for the financial years ending on 30 June 2016 (“FY2016”), 30 June 2017 (“FY2017”), and 30 June 2018 (“FY2018”). The Accused dealt with James Raj (“James”), a PAC director, and Hartasha Kaur (“Hartasha”), a PAC employee for this purpose. Hartasha prepared the draft consolidated financial statements for FY2016, FY2017 and FY2018, and emailed them to the Accused. The Accused knew that these consolidated financial statements had not been audited by PAC.

(b)     Separately, Tang Choon Foo (“Tang”), the auditor assigned by PAC to audit AIPL, had issued (in his official capacity) AIPL’s financial statements for FY2016, FY2017 and FY2018 (“audited FY2018 financial statements”). Unlike the draft financial statements prepared by Hartasha, the financial statements that Tang had issued were audited and non-consolidated. Further, they contained information on AIPL’s financials that were different from Hartasha’s drafts. Tang’s audited financial statements had also contained an auditor’s report which stated that PAC’s opinion was qualified. This is because from 2016 to 2018, AIPL had failed to provide Tang with relevant financial information of its overseas subsidiaries that he needed for the purpose of issuing audited and consolidated versions of AIPL’s financial statements.

(c)     Because of Tang’s refusal to issue unqualified consolidated financial statements, the draft (unaudited) consolidated financial statements for FY2016 and FY2017 prepared by Hartasha were subsequently falsified through the inclusions of an auditor’s report (“the falsified FY2016 and FY2017 financial statements”). Further, the falsified FY2017 financial statements included a statement which falsely claimed that the reviewing auditor’s opinion was unqualified.

Falsification charge

7       Regarding the falsification charge that the Accused had pleaded guilty, the circumstances are as follows. On 14 March 2019, the Accused forwarded Tang’s audited FY2018 financial statements to her deputy, Patrick Vincent L Lau (“Lau”). She told Lau that the audited FY2018 statements contained a qualified opinion from PAC, and that if the financial institutions were to receive these statements, they might cease extending credit facilities to AIPL. The Accused therefore instructed Lau to copy the signature in the audited FY2018 financial statements and insert it into another document that falsely purported to be AIPL’s audited and consolidated financial statements for FY2018. This document contained false information on AIPL’s financial position (“falsified FY2018 financial statements”). Lau complied with the Accused’s instructions. He took a screenshot of Tang’s signature from the audited FY2018 financial statements, pasted the signature into the falsified FY2018 financial statements, and then sent the falsified statements to the Accused.

Cheating charges

8       Regarding the 11 cheating charges which the Accused had pleaded guilty, it is not disputed that from January 2017 to November 2019, the Accused had instructed and/or authorised her subordinates to forward AIPL’s falsified financial statements to 11 financial institutions. She knew that these institutions would rely on the statements to assess AIPL’s credit facilities. Believing that the falsified financial statements were audited and accurately represented AIPL’s financial position, these institutions were induced into granting credit facilities to AIPL. The total credit facility granted in the 11 proceeded cheating charges is US$477,699,977.65 (S$647,904,479.69). The total losses suffered by the relevant financial institutions are US$414,438,104.26 (S$562,102,400.81).

9       Ng’s whereabouts is currently unknown, and no other person has been prosecuted in connection with the Accused’s offences.

Sentencing submissions

Prosecution’s submissions

10     The Prosecution’s submissions for the Accused’s cheating charges are as follows.

(a)     The key sentencing factors for cheating are harm and culpability.[note: 6]

(i)       In this case, the harm caused by the Accused’s offences is “very severe”. Apart from huge financial losses suffered by her victims, the Accused’s offences had also undermined confidence in the financial and economic ecosystem, increased the business costs, and could cause financial institutions to withdraw trade financing services and thus affect legitimate businesses.[note: 7]

(ii)       The Accused’s culpability would ordinarily be classified as “high” for the following reasons. First, she had “flagrantly” abused her position as the CFO of AIPL by instructing and authorising her subordinates to forge signatures and send falsified documents to the relevant financial institutions. Second, there was “significant premeditation and planning” in that the Accused had initially sought to obstruct Tang’s audit by asking his boss, James, to manage his repeated requests for information and documents to carry out his work. Third, the offences were committed on more than 30 occasions over three years. Furthermore, the falsified financial statements were complex and detailed documents – only someone with intimate knowledge of the AIPL and had access to its documents (which were voluminous) could detect the statements to be false. The Prosecution accepted that there is no evidence that the Accused had committed the offences out of greed. As such, this warranted a “sentencing discount” and the Accused’s culpability ought to be pegged at “moderate”.[note: 8]

(b)     According to the sentencing matrix in Public Prosecutor v Gene Chong Soon Hui [2018] SGDC 117 (“Gene Chong”) at [42] – [55], the indicative starting point sentence for a cheating offence involving severe harm and moderate culpability is 42 to 78 months’ imprisonment. Considering the amounts of monies cheated and the Accused’s level of culpability, the sentences for each charge should be as follows:[note: 9]

Amount cheated

Sentence

Between US$11 mil and US$24.5 mil

66 months

Between US$38 mil and US$50 mil

72 months

Between US$69 mil and US$100 mil

78 months



(c)     The proposed sentence of between 66 months to 78 months’ imprisonment for each cheating charge is in line with the sentencing precedents, namely, Public Prosecutor v Chia Teck Leng [2004] SGHC 68 (“Chia Teck Leng”), Public Prosecutor v Koh Seah Wee [2012] 1 SLR 292 (“Koh Seah Wee”), Public Prosecutor v Linda Lee [2017] SGDC 267 (“Linda Lee”), and Public Prosecutor v So Seow Tiong [2021] SGDC 203 (“So Seow Tiong”).[note: 10]

(d)     There is no need to adjust the sentences in [10(b)] for the offender-specific factors in the present case. This is because the mitigating effect of the Accused’s guilty plea is offset by (i) the significant number of cheating charges that had been taken into consideration for the purpose of sentencing and (ii) her attempt to evade prosecution by absconding from Singapore.[note: 11]

11     As for the Accused’s s 477A offence, the Prosecution submitted the sentencing range is between 12 to 36 months’ imprisonment where the property involved is between $150,000 to $5.4 mil. In the present case, a sentence in the middle of the sentencing range (i.e., at least 18 months’ imprisonment) would be appropriate given the presence of the following aggravating factors. First, the offence involves an abuse of the Accused’s role as AIPL’s CFO. Second, there was significant planning and premeditation in the commission of the offence. Finally, including the charges taken into consideration, the Accused had falsified at least 4 sets of documents.[note: 12]

Defence’s submissions

12     According to the Defence, the Accused’s culpability for her offences was lowered by the following factors:

(a)     Ng was the mastermind behind the offences. The Accused had merely followed his instructions when she (i) contacted James and Hartasha for the purpose of preparing the draft FY2016, FY2017 and FY2018 consolidated financial statements for AIPL and its subsidiaries,[note: 13] (ii) approached James regarding Tang’s repeated requests for voluminous documents and information when Tang was preparing AIPL’s financial statements, and (iii) caused Tang’s signature to be pasted it in the falsified financial statements.[note: 14] Ng was the one who handled the trades involved in the trade financing. The Accused did not know anything about these trades.[note: 15]

(b)     The Accused had committed the offences for two reasons. First, Ng was her long time superior. He had significant control and influence over her and had pressured her to commit the offences. The Accused had believed that Ng would be able to repay the financial institutions. Second, the Accused had committed the offences to keep AIPL afloat and its employees in employment. The Accused did not commit the offences for personal gain. On this basis, she deserved a 50% sentencing discount.[note: 16]

(c)     The offences were unsophisticated. The s 477A offence involved simply copying Tang’s signature onto a false document. No fake transactions were created as part of the sham. As for the cheating offences, there was no significant degree of premeditation or deception.[note: 17]

13     The Defence urged me to consider, as mitigating, the fact that the Accused (a) had pleaded guilty at the first opportunity, (b) is a first offender, (c) is elderly (63 years old at time of sentencing), and (d) is of poor health (she had a major heart operation in 2013, suffers from anxiety disorder, insomnia, and depression, and sometimes hears voices in her head).[note: 18]

14     The Defence submitted that –

(a)     The Accused’s s 477A offence is less serious than those in (i) Tan Puay Boon v Public Prosecutor [2003] 3 SLR(R) 390 (“Tan Puay Boon”) (sentences of between three to 18 months’ imprisonment for several counts of s 477A offences imposed).[note: 19]

(b)     The Accused ought to receive the same sentence as that imposed in Public Prosecutor v Ong Ah Huat (SC-903927-2020) (“Ong Ah Huat”)[note: 20] (nine years’ imprisonment) for her cheating offences.

Issues to be determined

15     The parties’ submissions raise several issues for determination. These include – What are the sentencing factors for offences under s 420 and s 477A of the Penal Code? Is the Accused entitled to a sentencing discount at a fixed percentage rate because she did not commit the offences for personal gain? How should the sentencing precedents for s 420 and s 477A be rationalised? I will now address these issues in turn.

My decision – Cheating charges

Offence-specific sentencing factors

16     I agree with the Prosecution that the offence-specific sentencing factors for a s 420 offence can usefully be grouped under the broad rubric of harm and culpability.

Factors relating to harm

17     In the case of financial fraud, the relevant harm factors include the following:

(a)     The value of the property cheated.

(b)     The extent of pecuniary loss suffered by the victim.

It bears noting that the extent of a victim’s actual loss may not always be the same as the value of the property cheated. The present case is a good example – the cheating had resulted in the grant of credit facilities (amount cheated) which is larger than the actual losses suffered by the financial institutions. The losses suffered is lower because of partial repayment of the facilities by AIPL as well as subsequent seizure and recovery of its assets pursuant to investigations

(c)     The extent of other harm caused by the cheating.

(i)       In the case of financial fraud, the resultant harm is not always confined to pecuniary losses only. Examples of non-pecuniary harm include inconvenience, embarrassment, and loss of reputation: Public Prosecutor v Fernando Payagala Waduge Malitha Kumar [2007] 2 SLR(R) 334 (“Fernando Payagala”) at [49] – [50].

(ii)       The harm that can potentially arise from a cheating offence also should be considered: Dong Guitian v Public Prosecutor [2004] 3 SLR(R) 34 at [40]. This would encompass all harm that can reasonably flow from the offence: Leong Sow Hon v Public Prosecutor [2021] 3 SLR 1199 at [35] and [36].

(iii)       Additionally, consideration of harm is not limited to that suffered by the immediate victim only. For instance, financial fraud against public and financial institutions –

… often have repercussions beyond the immediate facts of the case. New and more stringent checks may have to be introduced to try to prevent a repeat of the cheating. More levels of authorisation and authentication may have to be put in place. The result is increased costs in time, manpower and possibly infrastructure ... There is the added dimension of creating disputes and litigation among those deceived.

See Koh Seah Wee at [60]; Chia Teck Leng at [38] and [42]; Fernando Payagala at [49] and [50]; Tan Thiam Wee v Public Prosecutor [2012] 4 SLR 141 (“Tan Thiam Wee”) at [11].

Factors relating to culpability

18     An offender who is more entrenched in his criminality and is more blameworthy deserves a more severe sentence. Factors which can reflect these considerations include the following:

(a)     Motive for cheating.

The commission of an offence for financial gains is generally an aggravating factor: Vasentha d/o Joseph v Public Prosecutor [2015] 5 SLR 122 at [51].

(b)     Scale of the cheating

(i)       A good indicator of the scale of cheating is its duration and the number of victims cheated. For instance, it is aggravating if the cheating is prolonged, persistent, and systematic, committed on numerous instances, or involves many victims: Koh Seah Wee at [58].

(ii)       For completeness, I wish to add that the number of charges preferred against an offender is a poor indicator of the scale of cheating. There are several reasons for this. First, a single charge may involve cheating that spans a period and involves various acts of deception before the relevant property is eventually delivered. Indeed, the sentencing precedents in Annex A shows that there is no direct co-relation between the number of charges preferred and the scale of the cheating. Second, since 2018, it is legally permissible to amalgamate different offences of cheating into one charge: s 124(4) of the Criminal Procedure Code 2010 (“CPC”). This means that a single amalgamated charge will involve more than one distinct offence of cheating.

(c)     Manner and level of planning, premeditation, and sophistication of the cheating.

It is aggravating, for instance, where an offender commits the offence –

(i)       by leveraging on the features of the internet: Public Prosecutor v Syamsul Hilal bin Ismail [2012] 1 SLR 973,

(ii)       by abusing the trust reposed in him or his position: Koh Seah Wee at [57] – [59]),

(iii)       by exploiting a vulnerable victim,

(iv)       with a transnational element,

(v)       in collusion with other offender(s): Koh Seah Wee at [57]. In this last situation, the nature of the offender’s role and the extent of his level of awareness of the fraudulent activity are also relevant considerations: Koh Seah Wee at [58].

Offender-specific sentencing factors

19     Apart from the offence-specific sentencing factors, the offender-specific sentencing factors must also be considered. The latter includes the following:

(a)     The number of charges taken into consideration.

(b)     The offender’s extent of remorse for his offence.

(i)       Examples of remorse include the offender’s (1) voluntary surrender to the authorities, (2) acknowledgment of the seriousness of his offences, (3) full and frank disclosure of criminal activities beyond the offences for which he has been charged, (4) voluntary restitution, and (5) early plea of guilty.

(ii)       Examples of lack of remorse include the offender (1) disposing evidence of his offence after it has come to light, (2) taking actions to prevent the cheated property from being recovered, (3) absconding from Singapore, (4) re-offending while on bail, and (5) failing to take full responsibility for his offence (e.g., by attacking/blaming the victim for the offence).

See Sentencing Principles in Singapore (Academy Publishing, 2019) (“Sentencing Principles”) at Cap 20; Public Prosecutor v Siow Kai Yuan Terence [2020] SGHC 82 at [56]; Yuen Ye Ming v Public Prosecutor [2020] 2 SLR 970 at [62] and [63].

(c)     The offender has relevant antecedents, and his latest offence demonstrates recalcitrance.

Sentencing precedents

Analytical approach

20     I have summarised in Annex A the relevant sentencing precedents based on the sentencing factors stated in [17] – [19] above. I find this analytical approach helpful because parties tend to be selective and highlight only certain sentencing factors in a precedent that support their sentencing position. Annex A (a) allows one to compare the gravity of the offences in the precedents and the Accused’s case holistically based on all the relevant sentencing data points, and (b) avoids undue emphasis being given to any particular sentencing factor. The analytical approach taken in Annex A thus minimises the risk of one missing the woods for the trees in deciding on the appropriate sentence for the Accused.

21     At this juncture, I digress to make a few observations regarding the sentencing precedents.

Primary yardstick for sentencing

22     It has been held that the value of the property cheated is the “primary yardstick” for sentencing a cheating offence: Idya Nurhazlyn bte Ahmad Khir v Public Prosecutor [2014] 1 SLR 756 (“Idya Nurhazlyn”) at [48]. This approach makes instinctive sense because there is often a close relationship between –

(A)     the value of the property cheated,

(B)     the extent of the victim’s detriment caused by the cheating, and

(C)     the extent of the offender’s criminal benefits.

For instance, where X cheats Y into delivering $1,000, spends all the money on himself, and fails to make any restitution, the values of (A), (B) and (C) are the same.

23     It bears noting however that while the value of the property cheated is a convenient starting point for sentencing, it is not invariably the case that it has the same value as (B) and (C). For instance, it is possible that the victim may eventually not suffer any detriment because the offender returns all the cheated funds: see So Seow Tiong. The offender may also not have received any, or received only a partial amount, of the cheated funds: see Ong Ah Huat.

24     In the circumstances, as between (A), (B) and (C), I am of the view that greater weight should be given to (B) and (C) in sentencing.

Rationalising the precedents

25     The approach in [24] above allows us to better understand the sentencing precedents and reconcile the apparent sentencing discrepancies, for instance, (a) between So Seow Tiong and Linda Lee, and (b) between Ong Ah Huat and Chia Teck Leng. Let me explain.

26     First, the apparent discrepancies between So Seow Tiong and Linda Lee. Despite the funds cheated being relatively similar, the sentences in So Seow Tiong (six to 12 months per charge) are significantly lower than those in Linda Lee (one to 4.5 years per charge). This can be explained on the basis that actual pecuniary losses suffered by the victims in So Seow Tiong are significantly lower than those in Linda Lee. For convenience, the relevant factors in Annex A are summarised below:

27     I now come to the apparent discrepancies between Ong Ah Huat and Chia Teck Leng. In Ong Ah Huat, the value of the property cheated is US$320 mil. This value is much higher than that in Chia Teck Leng (S$117.1 mil). Yet, the sentence for the cheating charge in Ong Ah Hock (40 to 60 months’ imprisonment per charge) is lower than that in Chia Teck Leng (six years’ imprisonment per charge). This outcome can be rationalised when one considers the fact that (a) the value of the losses suffered and (b) the value of the benefits enjoyed by the offender in Ong Ah Huat are both lower than in Chia Teck Leng. The offender squandered most of the cheated funds on gambling. He lost at least S$62 m in the casinos. Being one of the biggest players in an Australian casino, he was provided with transport in a private jet whenever he wanted to gamble. The offender had also used the cheated funds to purchase a Mercedes Benz car and an apartment in Singapore. He had also given away more than S$300,000 in cash and gifts to various persons.

Restitution

28     Apart from allowing us to rationalise the sentencing precedents, there is another important purpose to using (a) the extent of the victim’s detriment and (b) the extent of the offender’s benefit for sentencing analysis – namely that this will incentivise offenders to make amends for their wrongdoing by voluntarily making restitution with a view of reducing their possible sentences.

The caveats

29     The sentencing approach in [24] above is subject to the following qualifications. First, while there is a proportionate relationship between (a) the victim’s pecuniary loss and the offender’s pecuniary benefit with (b) the severity of the sentence, this does not mean that this relationship is linear. This is because sentencing for cheating offences is not a mathematical exercise where the victim’s pecuniary loss and the offender’s pecuniary benefit are the only two sentencing considerations. As highlighted in [17] – [19], other sentencing factors are also relevant. Second, sentencing is a highly evaluative exercise where many discrete decisions must be made on the weight to be given to many sentencing factors to arrive at the ultimate sentence. Finally, the pecuniary loss suffered by a victim is not the only measure of harm caused by an offence. Other types of harm can also significantly affect sentencing: see [17(c)].

Sentences for the cheating charges

30     I now apply the above sentencing considerations to the present case.

Accused had benefitted indirectly from her offences

31     I begin with the parties’ submissions that the Accused did not derive any benefit from her offences.

32     I have some difficulty with this submission. It bears remembering that the Accused had committed the offences to keep AIPL afloat. If AIPL’s business had suffered or the company had become insolvent because it failed to secure trade financing, then this would surely have adversely affected the Accused – she would have either lost her job or suffered a pay cut. Because of her offences, AIPL was able to stay afloat, and this allowed the Accused to draw a princely salary of $32,000 per month (excluding bonuses).

Absence of motive for personal gain

33     The parties have also submitted that the Accused is entitled to a “sentencing discount” at a fixed rate because her offences were not motivated by personal gain. The Defence submitted for a 50% discount[note: 21] while the Prosecution submitted for a one-third discount.[note: 22]

34     In my view, it is wrong for the parties to submit for such a discount (whether it is one-third or 50%). My reasons are as follows:

(a)     It is well established that the mere absence of a motive of personal gain – on its own – is not a general mitigating factor: Lim Ying Ying Luciana v Public Prosecutor [2016] 4 SLR 1220 (“Lim Ying Ying”) at [52]. This is because a punishment seeks to deter a prohibited conduct. To recognise that the absence of a motive of personal gain per se warrants a sentencing discount is incompatible with this sentencing objective and can render the punishment ineffective and inadequate: Sentencing Principles at [17.141] – [17.147].

(b)     For the absence of a motive of personal gain to justify a reduction in sentence, it must be shown that the offence is ordinarily committed for personal gain: Lim Ying Ying at [52]. Where this is shown, then the sentence of an offender who did not commit an offence for personal gain will not be benchmarked against the sentencing precedents as they involve offenders who are more culpable: Kavitha d/o Mailvaganam v Public Prosecutor [2017] 4 SLR 1349 at [22], [26] and [27]. In the context of financial fraud, lower sentences have been imposed on offenders who offended out of a desire to either tide his company over a cashflow situation or keep his company afloat and his employees in employment: Tan Thiam Wee at [13] and [16]. That said, even in such cases, the sentence should still be sufficiently deterrent and retributive. This is especially so where the offence is premeditated and significant harm has been caused.

(c)     It bears noting that where a lower sentence is justified in the circumstances described in (b) above, the High Court has not specified a rate for sentencing discount where an offender is not motivated by personal gain to commit cheating. On the contrary, the High Court has stressed that it is still necessary to assess the weight to be given to this factor on the facts of the case: Lim Ying Ying at [54].

(d)     It is not meaningful to talk of a one-third or 50% sentencing discount rate in the present case when the starting point sentence for the purpose of computing the discount is not clear. There is no guideline judgement from the High Court setting out the tariff sentences for cheating offences. The sentencing tariffs in Gene Chong have not been endorsed by the High Court: Jennifer Toh Suat Leng v Public Prosecutor [2022] SGHC 146 at [74]. Cheating offences do not overwhelmingly manifest in a particular way, and it is not possible to discern from the sentencing precedents a clear sentencing benchmark or tariff that is applicable in the present case: Ng Kean Meng Terence v Public Prosecutor [2017] 2 SLR 449 at [31] – [32]. For completeness, I disagree with the Prosecution’s view that sentences imposed in the precedents represent the starting point or tariff sentences for cheating. This is because these sentences were imposed after a multi-factorial assessment of all the unique sentencing factors present in those cases.

(e)     Finally, a submission that the Accused is entitled to a one-third or 50% sentencing discount proceeds on the basis that the absence of a motive for personal gain, which is a culpability factor, is considered at the end of the sentencing analysis. Such an approach gives undue weight to the absence of personal gain in sentencing. In my view, a more principled sentencing approach is – (a) to consider the Accused’s lack of a motive of personal gain together with the other offence-specific sentencing factors (see [17] and [18] above) to derive the starting point sentence, and (b) to thereafter either enhance or discount the starting point sentence by considering the offender-specific factors (see [19] above) present in the Accused’s case.

Ong Ah Huat and Chia Teck Leng

35     I now come to the parties’ submissions on the sentencing precedents.

(a)     The Defence submitted that the Accused’s aggregate sentence should be similar to Ong Ah Huat (nine years’ imprisonment).[note: 23]

(b)     On the other hand, the Prosecution submitted that the indicative starting sentence based on the value of the cheated funds should be nine to 10 years’ imprisonment based on Chia Teck Leng. Applying a one-third discount to cater for the fact that the Accused’s offences were not motivated by personal gain, the Prosecution submitted for a sentence of 66 – 78 months’ imprisonment per charge.[note: 24]

37     Further, the Accused’s offences bear the following additional aggravating factors which are absent in Ong Ah Huat and Chia Teck Leng:

(a)      Lack of remorse. The Accused had taken steps to evade detection and apprehension.

(i)       According to the Prosecution, when some of the victims made further enquiries regarding the falsified financial statements, the Accused had taken “active steps to mask the fraud”. For instance, she had instructed a subordinate to enter false entries in AIPL’s internal balance sheets and management accounts. The Accused had also instructed another subordinate to draft a letter stating that the employee responsible for falsifying the submitted documents would be disciplined and dealt with internally. The Prosecution’s submission, which is based on two charges which the Accused had admitted and consented to be taken into consideration for the purpose of sentencing,[note: 26] has not been disputed by the Defence.

(ii)       Further, I note that shortly after CAD raided AIPL’s premises on 15 January 2020 at 10.03 am, the Accused left Singapore on 16 January 2020 at 12:02 am. She did not respond to CAD’s multiple attempts to contact her. The Accused had to be arrested by the United Arab Emirates (“UAE”) authorities and was returned to Singapore only on 17 September 2021. The fact that the Accused had absconded from Singapore is an aggravating factor: Lin Lifen v Public Prosecutor [2016] 1 SLR 287 at [50]; Public Prosecutor v Leong Soon Kheong [2009] 4 SLR(R) 63 at [50]. She had displayed a lack of remorse, wasted precious resources that had to be expended to locate her and to bring her back to Singapore, and caused justice to be delayed by 20 months. The Accused’s act of absconding undercut the mitigating value of her guilty plea.

(b)      National interests prejudiced. Further, the Accused’s offences had sent shock waves in the banking and commodity trading industries and had imperilled Singapore’s national interests. In its article “Commodity trading blow-ups dent Singapore’s reputation” published on 21 May 2020, the Financial Times reported that offences such as the Accused’s “had raised serious questions about the strength of Singapore’s regulatory framework and oversight of trading houses” and “[had threatened Singapore’s] ambition to become the world’s leading commodity trading hub”. Commodity trading accounts for 4.5% of Singapore's gross domestic product.[note: 27] Arising from a spate of commodity trade financing fraud cases (which included the Accused’s), a question was tabled in Parliament. On 5 October 2020, Tharman Shanmugaratnam, Senior Minister and Minister in charge of MAS, had to assure Members of Parliament as well as the banking and commodity trading industries that follow-up actions were being undertaken to prevent further fraudulent activities and restore confidence.

40     In my view, the above features in Chia Teck Leng are more than overshadowed by the numerous and far more aggravating sentencing factors in the Accused’s offences.

(a)     To use the Prosecution’s words, the Accused’s offences are “one of the largest and most complex fraudulent trade financing schemes ever to be prosecuted before the courts”.[note: 28] These offences (i) had involved four times more victims than in Chia Teck Leng, and (ii) had caused almost eight times more losses than in Chia Teck Leng. Unlike Chia Teck Leng, the Accused’s offences (iii) had undermined confidence in Singapore’s financial and economic ecosystem, and (iv) had threatened its ambition to be the world’s leading commodity trading hub.

(b)     Unlike the offender in Chia Teck Leng who had acted alone, the Accused had abused her position as a CFO and directed her staff to commit a fraud that persisted for three years.

(c)     The Accused’s offences are also more difficult to detect than those in Chia Teck Leng. I accept the Prosecution’s submissions the falsified financial statements in the present case are complex, and that only someone who has intimate knowledge of the AIPL and has access to its internal records could have detected the fraud. The complexity of the Accused’s offences is also evident from the fact that based on court records, the investigations were concluded only in June 2022, i.e., some nine months after she was returned to Singapore.

(d)     Another significant difference between the two cases is the degree of remorse shown by the offenders. When his offences came to light, the offender in Chia Teck Leng had cooperated with the authorities and had helped to recover 30% of the cheated funds. The Accused did not do likewise. Instead, she absconded from Singapore. During the 20 months when the Accused remained at large, the authorities and her victims had to piece together what had happened and pick up the pieces.

41     In Chia Teck Leng, the High Court imposed six years’ imprisonment on each of the offender’s cheating charges. This is close to the maximum punishment of seven years’ imprisonment at the material time.

42     Given the numerous and far more aggravating factors in the Accused’s offences, the maximum sentence of 10 years’ imprisonment would have been appropriate for each of her offences involving higher amounts of cheated funds – but for the following factors:

(a)     The Accused is not the mastermind behind the cheating offences. The Accused had committed the offences on Ng’s instructions. I accept the Defence’s submission that the Accused did not know the details of the underlying trades and drawdowns from the credit facilities.

(b)     The Accused’s offences were not motivated by greed. She had committed the offences to keep AIPL afloat and its employees in employment.

43     While the above two factors are relevant to ensure proportionality and parity in sentencing as well as to explain why the maximum sentence is not imposed on the Accused, it would be wrong to treat them as justifying sentences lower than those in Ong Ah Huat and Chia Teck Leng given the consideration in [36] – [38] above as well as the following factors:

(a)     As the Prosecution had rightly pointed out, the Accused had 30 years of working experience and was one of the top executives in a global trading house. She would have known from the outset that what she was instructed to do was illegal. She could have refused to comply with Ng’s instructions, and if needed, leave AIPL. Instead, she chose to assist Ng in perpetuating the cheating scam and gave the necessary instructions to several of her subordinates to spin the web of deceit to defraud numerous financial institutions for a lengthy period. Cheating is a choice: Public Prosecutor v Muhammad Nazri bin Sapar [2022] SGDC 273 at [12(a)]. The Accused had chosen to commit her offences with her eyes wide open.

(b)     While there is no evidence that the Accused had received any of the cheated funds, it would be wrong to say that she did not benefit from it in anyway either. See [32] above.

My decision – Falsification charge

46     I now come to the Accused’s charge under s 477A. The offence is punishable with imprisonment for a term which may extend to 10 years, or with fine, or with both.

Offence-specific sentencing factors

47     The sentencing factors for a s 477A offences have been discussed in several cases. Many of these factors are similar to those for s 420 of the Penal Code.

Factors relating to culpability

48     A non-exhaustive list of the sentencing factors relating to an offender’s culpability for the offence is as follows:

(a)     Motive for the offence.

There can be various reasons why an offender would commit a s 477A offence. These include the following:

(i)       To commit another crime: see e.g., Public Prosecutor v Foo Jierong [2022] SGDC 118 (“Foo Jierong”) at [122] (to cheat the tax authorities into disbursing grants); Phang Wah v Public Prosecutor [2012] 1 SLR 646 at [86] (to defraud the tax authorities into imposing a lesser tax liability); Public Prosecutor v Yang Yin [2016] SGDC 279 at [10] – [12], [52] and [54] (to defraud the immigration authorities into issuing an employment pass and permanent residency status); Public Prosecutor v Kwa Tian Hwa [2017] SGDC 119 (“Kwa Tian Hwa”) (to defraud an accomplice’s company into making reimbursements to the accomplice based on fictitious claims); and Public Prosecutor v Chew Soo Chun [2016] 2 SLR 78 (“Chew Soo Chun”) (to defraud a bank into granting loans to the offender’s company to keep it afloat). Where the crime is financial fraud, then this would frequently be for the purpose of securing a pecuniary gain or avoiding a pecuniary loss. In such cases, the value of the gain/loss would be a relevant sentencing consideration. The fact that an offender was not motivated by personal gain is a relevant sentencing consideration: Public Prosecutor v Lam Leng Hung [2017] SGHC 71 (“Lam Leng Hung”) at [416]; Tan Puay Boon at [47]; Public Prosecutor v Kidd, David John [2020] SGHC 230 (“Kidd”) at [37], [48] and [51]; Public Prosecutor v Aw Meng Choo Joanna [2006] SGDC 219 (“Aw Meng Choo”) at [177(d)].

(ii)       To cover up a crime, wrongdoing, or administrative breach: see e.g., Lam Leng Hung (to cover up the commission of offences under s 409 of the Penal Code); Public Prosecutor v Tan Boon Gee [2015] SGDC 90 (to conceal the payment of a bribe); Public Prosecutor v Low Xin Yi [2018] SGDC 79 (“Low Xin Yi”) (to cover up the commission of offences under s 408 of the Penal Code); Gene Chong at [8] (to cover up the commission of offences under s 420 of the Penal Code); Public Prosecutor v Li Yong De [2021] SGDC 115 (“Li Yong De”) at [76] (to conceal misappropriation of employer’s properties); Public Prosecutor v Nithiya d/o Harithas [2021] SGDC 128 at [215] (to disguise payments which the offender had wrongfully caused to be made from her employer’s funds); Tan Puay Boon at [49] (to conceal unauthorised drawings which the offender had made from her employer’s funds); Tan Liang Chye at [14] and [16] (to camouflage the sale of diverted electronic scrap in breach of a contractual agreement); Kidd (to cover up trading losses); Goh Kah Heng v Public Prosecutor [2010] 4 SLR 258 at [95] (to mask the giving of an unauthorised loan); and Public Prosecutor v Leow Ban Leong [2018] SGDC 157 (“Leow Ban Leong”) at [163] (to cover up a breach of procurement conditions). The nature of the misconduct that the offender seeks to cover up is relevant to the extent of an offender’s culpability. For instance, an offender who commits a s 477A offence to cover up the fact that he has inadvertently overcharged his client, and not because he had cheated or deliberately overcharged his client, is less culpable: Leow Ban Leong at [163]. The severity of the possible punishment or other consequences that the offender seeks to avoid is also a relevant sentencing consideration. All things being equal, the level of culpability is generally lower where a s 477A offence is committed to cover up a past misconduct than one where the offence is committed to enable the offender to obtain future pecuniary or other material gains: Kidd at [37].

(iii)       To evade administrative oversight: see e.g., Public Prosecutor and Lim Lee Eng Jansen [2001] SGDC 188 at [57] (to defraud employer-bank into granting additional unauthorised credit facilities to its client); and Public Prosecutor v Sim Ee Tong [2006] SGDC 296 (“Sim Ee Tong”) (to defraud independent auditors who were auditing a company’s financial health). It is an aggravating factor where the oversight mechanism sought to be evaded is imposed to protect the public. One such example is the offence is to circumvent disclosure regime imposed by the Singapore Exchange: see Kidd at [55].

(iv)       To comply with instructions or pressure from the offender’s superior or out of a misguided sense of loyalty to a co-offender: Aw Meng Choo at [177(c)].

(b)     Scale of the falsification

It is aggravating where the offence is systematic and committed over a prolonged period or over many occasions: Tan Puay Boon at [47]; Kidd at [20], [37] and [43]; Kwa Tian Hwa at [226]; and Sim Ee Tong at [22] and [23].

(c)     Manner and level of planning, premeditation, and sophistication of the falsification.

It is aggravating if there is “deviousness or surreptitious planning” in the commission of the offence (Tan Puay Boon at [47]; Kwa Tian Hwa at [226]), or where the offender has acted in conspiracy with others (Tan Liang Chye; Kidd at [56] and [57]). In the case of a conspiracy, the offender’s role in the conspiracy is a relevant sentencing factor: Public Prosecutor v Takayoshi Wada [2009] SGDC 162 as discussed in Kidd at [38] – [43].

(d)     The degree of abuse of trust by the offender

(i)       A s 477A offence may be committed by someone who has no formal appointment in a victim-organisation: see e.g., Aw Meng Choo at [177(f)].

(ii)       Where an offender has a formal appointment in the victim-organisation, his level of seniority and role in the organisation are relevant to the degree of trust that has been abused. An offence is generally more serious, for instance, when it is committed by a senior officer (than when committed by a junior officer), or by an offender who plays a critical role in the management of the relevant document or record: Tan Puay Boon at [47]; Kidd at [21], [37] and [43]; Kwa Tian Hwa at [226]; and Low Xin Yi at [143(a)].

Factors relating to harm

49     The impact of the offence, if any, is also a relevant sentencing consideration: Sim Ee Tong at [21].

(a)     An offence is less serious where it has not proceeded beyond the mere preparation of the false document (e.g., because the offence is disrupted by investigations) and thus has not caused any harm: Aw Meng Choo at [177(g)] and Foo Jierong.

(b)     Where a s 477A offence is committed to cover up a crime, wrongdoing, or an administrative breach (“misconduct”), it is important not to conflate the harm caused by such misconduct with the harm caused by the s 477A offence. For instance, where a s 477A offence is committed to cover up a criminal breach of trust, the harm caused by the s 477A offence is the possible pervasion of the course of justice. The s 477A offence does not cause financial loss to the victim. Such a loss is caused by the criminal breach of trust: Low Xin Yi at [149].

(c)     Where a s 477A offence causes detriment to the victim (e.g., the falsified document causes a wrongful disbursements of funds), the extent of that detriment can affect the severity of the sentence: Aw Meng Choo at [177(h)]. One example where an offender’s s 477A offences had a devastating effect on the victim, and thus constituted a serious aggravating factor, is Li Yong De. In that case, the offender’s misdeeds left his employer (the victim) on the brink of insolvency.

(d)     It is an aggravating factor where a s 477A offence is intended to defraud a public agency: Foo Jierong at [117] and [118]; Sentencing Principles at [16.148] – [16.156].

(e)     The harm caused by a s 477A offence can extend beyond the immediate victim. For instance, where the offence is part of a large scale fraud which has deceived the victim-company’s shareholders and investing public: Public Prosecutor v Alex Ng Soon Heng [2010] SGDC 242; Sim Ee Tong at [23]; Kidd at [54] and [55]; Aw Meng Choo at [176(c)]. In some cases, the national interest, such as the integrity of Singapore’s financial system, may also be impacted: Public Prosecutor v Tan Liang Chye [2006] SGDC 109 (“Tan Liang Chye”) at [17]; Kwa Tian Hwa at [226].

(f)     It bears noting that s 477A of the Penal Code covers a wide range of acts. The actus reus requirement of the offence is met when a person destroys, alters, conceals, mutilates, falsifies, makes or abets the making of any false entry in, or omits or alters or abets the omission or alteration of any material particular from or in any document or record. An offence is more serious when the acts involve the destruction of a document, record or information that cannot be recovered.

Offender-specific sentencing factors

50     The offender-specific sentencing factors set out in [19] above are also applicable to a s 477A offence.

Sentencing precedents

51     The parties have cited four cases as reference points for calibrating the sentence for the Accused s 477A charge. These are Kwa Tian Hwa; Tan Liang Chye; Chew Soo Chun; Tan Puay Boon; Li Yong De. The relevant sentencing factors for these cases are set out at Annex B. It is difficult to discern from Annex B a clear sentencing trend. This is not surprising given the diverse factual scenarios in which s 477A offences can be committed.

Sentence for falsification charge

52     Of all the precedents cited to me, I find Chew Soo Chun to be the closest comparator. For instance, both the offender in Chew Soo Chun and the Accused–

(a)     Had committed their s 477A offences for the purpose of facilitating financial fraud, namely, to cheat financial institutions into providing financing to the offenders’ company;

(b)     Did not use any of the credit facilities provided from their offences for personal gain;

(c)     Had held very senior positions in their respective company;

(d)     Had instructed their subordinates to falsify the relevant documents;

(e)     Were first offenders and had pleaded guilty;

(f)     Had failed to make any restitution; and

(g)     Are not in good health. The offender in Chew Soo Chun suffered from more severe medical conditions than the Accused.

53     I am mindful that the offender in Chew Soo Chun had faced more charges and had held a more senior position in the company than the Accused. I also note that unlike the Accused, the offender in Chew Soo Chun was the mastermind behind the s 477A offences.

54     Nonetheless, I am of the view that the Accused’s s 477A offence is far more serious than those in Chew Soo Chun. I come to this view based on the following considerations:

55     Based on all the sentencing factors in the Accused’s offence as well as the sentence imposed in Chew Soo Chun (12 to 18 months’ imprisonment per charge), I impose a sentence of three years’ imprisonment on the Accused’s s 477A charge.

Aggregate sentence

One-transaction rule

56     I order the sentences for three of the s 420 charges (10th, 16th and 30th charges) to run consecutively. In my judgement, this order does not offend the one-transaction rule. The offences in the three charges were committed on different dates and involved different victims.

57     I have decided not to order the sentence for the s 477A charge to run consecutively with the rest. First, there was no recommendation to do so by the parties. Second and in any event, the act in the s 477A charge is an integral part of some of the s 420 offences. The s 477A offence is in essence part of the same criminal enterprise as the s 420 offences. Ordering the sentence for the s 477A charge to run concurrently will avoid the offender being doubly punished: Lam Leng Hung at [416]; s 40 of the Interpretation Act 1965; s 308 of the CPC; Wu Zhi Yong v Public Prosecutor [2021] SGHC 261 at [56] – [61]; Public Prosecutor v Raveen Balakrishnan [2018] 5 SLR 799 (“Raveen”) at [91] – [94] and [98]; Mohamed Shouffee bin Adam v Public Prosecutor [2014] 2 SLR 998 (“Shouffee”) at [78] and [79].

59     The aggregate sentence imposed is 20 years’ imprisonment. This is the maximum of my sentencing jurisdiction: s 303(2)(a) read with s 306(4) of the CPC.

60     I am of the view that the aggregate sentence does not offend the totality principle.

(a)     The totality principle has two limbs. First, the court must examine whether the aggregate sentence is substantially above the normal level of sentences for the most serious of the individual offences committed (“first limb”). Second, the court must examine whether the effect of the aggregate sentence on the offender is crushing and not in keeping with his past record and future prospects (“second limb”): Raveen at [73], citing Shouffee at [54] and [57].

(b)     Regarding the first limb, the most serious of the individual offences committed by the Accused is the 16th charge. The funds cheated came to US$100 mil and the financial institution concerned suffered a loss of about US$96.8 mil. There is no sentencing precedent for such an offence. The closest comparator is Chia Teck Leng, where six years’ imprisonment was imposed for cheating US$30 mil.[note: 29] Given that the total funds cheated in the Accused’s offences (US$586.5 mil) is almost 20 times of that in the closest comparator (US$30 mil), it cannot be said that the aggregate sentence of 20 years’ imprisonment is substantially above the normal level of sentences for the most serious of the individual offences committed (six years’ imprisonment).

(c)     As for the second limb, I am mindful that the Accused is elderly (63 years old at time of sentencing). With remission and backing of sentence, she will be about 76 years old by the time she is released from prison. The effect of the sentence will not be crushing on the Accused. Courts have imposed long sentences on elderly offenders before, whereby they would be in their 70s and 80s by the time they were released from prison. See for instance Chia Teck Leng (where the High Court had imposed 42 years’ imprisonment on a 45-year-old offender); Ewe Pang Kooi v Public Prosecutor [2020] 1 SLR 757 at [10] (where the Court of Appeal upheld a sentence of 25 years and 10 months’ imprisonment on a 66-year-old offender); Public Prosecutor v Soh Chee Wen (CC No. 9 of 2019) (where the High Court imposed 36 years’ imprisonment on a 62-year-old offender, Penny stock crash mastermind John Soh gets 36 years’ jail, Quah Su-Ling sentenced to 20 years, reported in the Straits Times, 29 December 2022).

(d)     In any event, it is settled law that the gravity of an offender’s offences and the principles of deterrence can operate to override the mitigating value of his advanced age: Ewe Pang Kooi v Public Prosecutor [2022] SGHC 300 at [62]. Given the gravity of the Accused’s offences, I am of the view that her advanced age carries little weight in sentencing.

Fine and compensation

61     For completeness, I wish to add that I have considered whether it is appropriate to also impose a fine and to make an order for the payment of compensation under s 359 of the CPC. I eventually decided against making the order because there is no evidence that the Accused had received the cheated funds. There is also no evidence that she will be able to pay the fine and compensation (if imposed) which are likely to be significant.

Conclusion

62     Finally, I order that the sentence be backdated to the date when the Accused was placed in the custody of the Singapore authorities, i.e., 17 September 2021.[note: 30]
